Before evaluating the GSAs based on the experimentally acquired data, it is good to appropriately conceive the experiments themselves through an “experimental design” [328, 329, 352–354]. Accordingly, one has to identify the factors influencing the responses (features) of the SA in a screening process. The most relevant factors in gas sensing are the target analyte concentration and the influence of the main interferents (like humidity, concentration of the known gases in the sample, temperature and pressure). A good experimental design must provide a choice of factors to be considered and the number of experimental events (including replicates) needed for correct GSA characterization [352, 353]. Response surface methodologies are often employed. They consider that the response xm, n of a given sensor n, in the experimental event number m (a certain gas exposure for instance), to the selected factors {fi} (gas concentrations for example) can be approximated through a polynomial of low order, containing linear and quadratic terms [323, 355]:1xm,n≅∑i=1,j=1,ki,j=0i=I,j=I,ki+kj≤2cm,n,i,j·fm,iki·fm,jkj\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
