				\begin{document}$$ s\cong \left({\sum}_{m=1}^M{c}_m\cdotp {x}_m\right)/\left({\sum}_{m=1}^M{\left({x}_m\right)}^2\right) $$\end{document}

Here, the scalar s is the sensor sensitivity and ex the error-vector of responses. The index 1 of the first rank column matrices (expressing only one feature) was omitted. Because the task of the sensors is to provide the value of the factor (concentration) when the feature (response) is known, one needs to consider an inverse calibrationc = b ∙ x + ec, where ec is the error-vector of concentrations. In the limit of experimental errors, b is the inverse of the sensitivity, and its estimation is given by:7b≅∑m=1Mcm·xm/∑m=1Mxm2\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
